Scenario 1: Identify Consistent High Performers

Question
Find employees who are receiving high salaries consistently.

Tables Used
employees

Logic Explanation
Use the employees table.
Check employees with higher salaries.
Sort salaries in descending order.

Employees with top salaries are considered high performers.

SQL Query
SELECT employee_id, name, salary
FROM employees
WHERE salary > 50000
ORDER BY salary DESC;

Result:

| employee_id | name    | salary |
| ----------- | ------- | ------ |
| 3           | Michael | 75000  |
| 1           | John    | 60000  |
| 4           | Sara    | 56000  |


============

Scenario 2: Customer Retention Analysis
Question

Find customers who made purchases recently.

Tables Used

sales
customers

Logic Explanation
Use the sales table to identify customer purchases.
Join with customers table using customer_id.
Filter customers based on recent purchase dates.

SQL Query
SELECT c.customer_name, s.amount, s.sale_date
FROM customers c
JOIN sales s
ON c.customer_id = s.customer_id
WHERE s.sale_date >= '2023-03-15';

| customer_name | amount | sale_date  |
| ------------- | ------ | ---------- |
| John Doe      | 4500   | 2023-03-15 |
| Jane Smith    | 5500   | 2023-03-16 |
| Alice Johnson | 7000   | 2023-03-17 |
| NULL          | 3000   | 2023-03-18 |
| Robert Brown  | 6000   | 2023-03-19 |

