Scenario 5: Detect Duplicate Records

Question
Find duplicate customer names.

Tables Used
customers

Logic Explanation
Group records using GROUP BY.
Count customer names using COUNT(*).
Use HAVING to identify duplicates.

SQL Query
SELECT customer_name, COUNT(*) AS duplicate_count
FROM customers
GROUP BY customer_name
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

Result:

| customer_name              | duplicate_count |
| -------------------------- | --------------- |
| No duplicate records found |                 |

=========

Scenario 6: Identify Products with No Sales

Question
Find products that do not appear in sales records.

Tables Used
products
sales

Logic Explanation
Use LEFT JOIN between products and sales.
Products without matching sales records will return NULL.
Filter NULL values to identify unsold products.

SQL Query
SELECT p.product_id, p.product_name
FROM products p
LEFT JOIN sales s
ON p.product_id = s.sale_id
WHERE s.sale_id IS NULL;

Result:

| product_id                                  | product_name |
| ------------------------------------------- | ------------ |
| No unsold products found in current dataset |              |


===========



